pr_review_body:
LGTM :+1: 
@codesankalp thanks for this

P.S. :- I made some minor changes in the build to maintain uniformity with other repositories.

Thanks for addressing this! I was going to work on a fix, but I'm so glad that you were able to fix these issues yourselves.

I like the detail that you have in your PR summary; I think that this should be captured in code as comments (especially your thorough breakdown of the new `SECRET` regex rationale).

With regards to test cases, I want to abandon the "old-style" tests, and (eventually) replace them with much more readable tests. After all, readable tests are a great way of documenting intended usage of functions. I think you have a good set of test cases, and maybe my interim test cases will help you get started?

```python
def test_ignore_case():
    secret = next(scan_line('os.environ["AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY"] = "testing"'))
    assert secret.secret_value == 'testing'


def test_secret_with_whitespace():
    secret = next(scan_line('password = "not a secret"'))
    assert secret.secret_value == 'not a secret'


def test_comparison_operator():
    secret = next(scan_line('api_key == "hunter2"'))
    assert secret.secret_value == 'hunter2'


def test_bounds():
    for index, secret in scan_line(
        'detect-secrets scan '
        '--exclude-lines "password = blah" '
        '--exclude-lines "password = fake"',
    ):
        assert secret.secret_value in {'blah', 'fake'}

    # TODO(2021-03-03): This should probably yield `fake` as well.
    # assert index == 1


def test_backticks():
    secret = next(scan_line('api_key = `cat password`'))

    assert secret.secret_value == 'cat password'


@pytest.mark.parametrize(
    'line',
    (
        'if ("value" == password)',
        'else if ("value" === password)',
        ...
    ),
)
def test_preceded_by_equals_sign(line):
    pass


@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)
def use_keyword_detector():
    with transient_settings({
        'plugins_used': [{
            'name': 'KeywordDetector',
        }],
    }):
        yield
```

Good try @yashikajotwani12 
But I think you and we are missing something important here.

@yashikajotwani12  needs to add [openwisp-utils](https://github.com/openwisp/openwisp-utils) in the requirements to run these checks. @nemesisdesign and @pandafy What do you say?

@Bruce-8 you've found the right idea to do the check, but as I was reviewing I realized there may be other messages from pycodestyle that contain the text "blank line".

Indeed, if you look at their [documentation page](https://pycodestyle.pycqa.org/en/latest/intro.html#error-codes) under "E3" you'll see a few different ones. So, I'd like to expand the scope of this PR to include good rendering for *all* "blank line" messages that pycodestyle displays. This means you'll need to be able to reproduce each one to test; note that the lines may need to be highlighted differently.

Additionally, this could be a good place for some custom "instruction" strings, similar to the missing module/docstring custom renderers. Why don't you play around with that and try to figure out what looks good (and run your ideas by the PythonTA team).

@markotoplak This is great! 

I have to admit it feels strange to have so much extra complication just for the `Constant` model but if it works 🤷‍♂️

I tested it with the default WidgetPreview data and 4 Voigt peaks (which are slow) and it stays responsive the whole time. So much so that it's impossible to tell the preview is running! Can we tap into the `progress_interrupt`/`set_progress_value()` stuff in the preview thread?

Race condition still exists. Are we just deferring that?

We can also use an atomic.Pointer instead of a lock if we're okay with optimistically loading information. If two goroutines compete, they'll both do the work and one of them will win.

```go
type localStack struct {
  // ...
  snapshot atomic.Pointer[*deploy.Snapshot]
}

func (s *localStack) Snapshot(...) (*deploy.Snapshot, error) {
  if v := s.snapshot.Load(); v != nil { return *v, nil }

  // ...

  snap, err := ...
  // ...
  s.snapshot.Store(&snap)
  return snap, nil
}
```
